---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import SocialIcon from '../../components/SocialIcon.astro';
import { AUTHOR, SITE_NAME, SITE_URL } from '../../consts';
import { absUrl } from '../../utils/images';

const authorUrl = new URL(AUTHOR.url, SITE_URL).href;
const imageUrl = absUrl(AUTHOR.image);

const jsonLd = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'Person',
  name: AUTHOR.name,
  url: authorUrl,
  image: imageUrl,
  jobTitle: AUTHOR.jobTitle,
  description: `Editor of ${SITE_NAME}. Full-time traveler with on-the-ground experience in ${AUTHOR.countriesVisited} countries.`,
  worksFor: {
    '@type': 'NewsMediaOrganization',
    name: SITE_NAME,
    url: SITE_URL,
  },
  sameAs: AUTHOR.sameAs,
};
---

<BaseLayout
  title={`${AUTHOR.name}, Editor`}
  description={`${AUTHOR.name} is an editor of ${SITE_NAME}. Full-time traveler with on-the-ground experience across ${AUTHOR.countriesVisited} countries.`}
  ogImage={AUTHOR.image}
  ogImageWidth={500}
  ogImageHeight={500}
  jsonLd={jsonLd}
>
  <article class="article author-page">
    <header class="author-header">
      <img
        class="author-photo"
        src={AUTHOR.image}
        alt={`${AUTHOR.name}`}
        width="160"
        height="160"
      />
      <div class="author-header__text">
        <h1>{AUTHOR.name}</h1>
        <p class="author-role">Editor, {SITE_NAME}</p>
        <ul class="author-social">
          {
            AUTHOR.social.map((item) => (
              <li>
                <a
                  class="social-link"
                  href={item.href}
                  target="_blank"
                  rel="noopener noreferrer me"
                  aria-label={item.label}
                  title={item.label}
                >
                  <SocialIcon network={item.id} />
                </a>
              </li>
            ))
          }
        </ul>
      </div>
    </header>

    <div class="article__body">
      <p>
        {AUTHOR.name} is an editor of {SITE_NAME}. He focuses on what a news
        story means if you have a real trip planned: your flights, border
        crossings, hotels, or whether you should change your plans or not.
      </p>
      <p>
        That lens comes from living on the road since 2018. He has lived on six
        continents and visited{' '}
        <strong>{AUTHOR.countriesVisited} countries</strong> so far. Hundreds of
        flights and long stays in places from Georgia, Bulgaria or Thailand to
        Southeast Asia, Africa, and Latin America mean a lot of the “what this
        means on the ground” framing here is very often based on real life
        experience there at some point.
      </p>
      <p>
        If a story is about a place he was in recently, he uses what he actually
        saw on the ground: how quiet tourist areas got when bookings dried up,
        what locals and guides were saying, how useful embassy alerts were next
        to local news, and the practical stuff like cash, passports, and backup
        routes when plans change. That has included places as different as
        Jordan during the 2026 Middle East conflict and Sri Lanka after the 2019
        attacks.
      </p>
      <p>
        He also knows the logistics side of long-term travel: second residency,
        banking across countries, visas, and what borders feel like when plans
        change fast. He studied structural engineering at Université Laval and
        was a member of the Ordre des ingénieurs du Québec for more than a
        decade. He now applies that same analytical mindset to analyze the news
        in a more practical way.
      </p>
      <p>
        Kevin is also a cofounder of{' '}
        <a href="https://flytrippers.com/">Flytrippers</a>, which covers travel
        rewards, flight deals, and travel tips.
      </p>
      <p>
        Originally from Québec. Featured in Canadian media including CBC’s{' '}
        <a href="https://www.cbc.ca/dragonsden/pitches/flytrippers"
          ><em>Dragons’ Den</em></a
        > with Flytrippers cofounder Andrew D’Amours.
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
